  "doc_id": "6755",
  "text": "Sayeed et al. [CITATION_1] advocate the use of real applications for benchmarking in HPC, and that small benchmarks cannot predict the behavior of the real HPC applications. They discuss important questions, challenges, tools and metrics in evaluating performance using HPC applications. Afterwards, they evaluate the performance of four application benchmarks on three different parallel architectures, and measure the runtime, inter-process communication overhead, I/O characteristics and memory footprint. This way, they show the importance of reporting various metrics, in order to have a better representation of application and system performance. Since they measure these metrics on several numbers of execution processes, the results differ from one execution to another. It is clear from their results that on different numbers of execution processes, different platforms perform better or worse, which can significantly bias the analysis on certain scale of the experiments.",
